d, <i>Alger</i> may be a variant of   Algeo  .","German: from a shortened form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adalgar</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Aulgur","meanings":["English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Auger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Gaston, Lucien, Marcel, Mederic, Normand, Raoul, Cecile, Emile, Fernand, Gaetan.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Auger</i>, which can be from ancient Germanic <i>Adalgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gaira-</i> ‘lance, spear’, or <i>Albgari</i>, with the first element <i>alb</i> ‘elf’. Compare   Auge  ,   Oge  ,   Ogea  , and   Osier  .","English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Algar","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Algar</i>, representing the falling together of two Old English names, <i>Ælfgār</i> and <i>Æthelgār</i>, composed of the elements respectively <i>ælf</i> ‘elf’ or <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gār</i> ‘spear’. It could also be from the much rarer Old English personal name <i>Ealdgār</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘old’ + ‘spear’. In East Anglia, it is more probably a variant of   Alger   (Old Norse <i>Álfgeirr</i>). See also   Agar  ,   Elgar  ."]},{"name":"Alker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerhart.","South German: variant of   Alger  .","English: habitational name from Altcar, Lancashire. This name means ‘marshland by the River Alt’, from Old Norse <i>kjarr</i> ‘marsh’ and the river name <i>Alt</i>."]},{"name":"Ager","meanings":["English (mainly Essex, Suffolk, and Northamptonshire): variant of   Alger   or possibly of   Edgar  .","Danish: habitational name from any of several places called Ager, meaning ‘plowed land’ (from a cognate of the English word <i>acre</i>).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gari</i> (from <i>garwa</i>) ‘ready, eager’ or <i>gari</i> ‘spear’. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Alger was born in 1260, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mrs William Alger."},"et":{"1260–":"1260–Surnud","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","1293–Male":"1293–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–":"1260–Kuollut","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","1293–Male":"1293–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1260–":"1260–Décédé","1262–Female":"1262–Décédée","1293–Male":"1293–Décédé","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Alger est né en 1260, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs William Alger."},"de":{"1260–":"1260–Verstorben","1262–Female":"1262–Verstorben","1293–Male":"1293–Verstorben","1260–Male":"1260–Verstorben","1262":"1262",